They say, the cheapest land is the most fertile and Kenya must be the most fertile land because every house and business has the foundation and the room for four walls except the house or building is not there. Nairobi also has the added beauty of dust the finer land particles getting through your nasal passages with every breath but only for a short amount of time. Here, the dirt particles get into every part of your body. The dust is usually sweeping off the back wheels of a boda boda or yellow top.

Riding a boda boda or a motorcycle taxi is interesting. The roads are not what someone who would be driving on them would consider safe but feeling every speed bump in the road and coming closer to the explosion that is motor vehicle collision helps you become more aware of the deadly metal in front of you. I am not driving a motor vehicle there. Yellow Tops are common in Malawi and the standard price for one person is 500 kwacha both ways. The price to me from a kettle headed to where I am flying to is 1500 kwacha.

My first full moving day here in Nairobi was a day I will never forget and not because they were moving furniture or a TV. It was moving day because this was the day that finally allowed me to meet the two people of pure sunshine in my world – Codee and Michael . They welcomed me with cocoa pops and Lipton
